Confirmed the exact causation:
- `CW_AGENT_STREAM` **unset** → test passes.
- `CW_AGENT_STREAM=0` (the ambient state the gate ran under) → test fails at line 107.

I now have everything needed for a verdict.

---

# REJECTED — release v0.1.94

## Verdict
The deterministic release gate **FAILS** in this release environment. I ran `bash plugins/cool-workflow/scripts/release-gate.sh` exactly once: it exited **1** at step `[2/6] tests` (`GATE FAIL: tests failed`). A release whose own gate is RED cannot be certified, regardless of how good the vendor work is.

## What the release contains (verified, and it is genuinely substantive)
This is *not* a thin release. Across `v0.1.93..HEAD` (3 commits, +879/−85) it:
- Fixes `codex-agent.js` against codex 0.139 (drops the removed `exec --ask-for-approval`, reads model from `$CODEX_HOME/config.toml`).
- Rewrites the `opencode-agent.js` JSON parser for the new `{type,part}` event shape and positional message arg; routes deepseek + gemini through it via thin `deepseek-agent.js` / `gemini-opencode-agent.js` shims.
- Adds `vendor-preflight.js`, a live hard-block gate wired into `release-flow.js` as step `[1b/3]`.
- The new tests (`vendor-preflight-smoke.js`, `deepseek-agent-wrapper-smoke.js`, `release-flow-smoke.js` cut cases) are real discriminators — they assert exit codes, model selection, and "blocks BEFORE the reviewer"; they would fail if the implementation were reverted. No dead spec fields (`lastMessageId`/`lastMessageText` are read at `opencode-agent.js:157`). Direction is squarely on North-Star Track C (multiple live LLM clients).

So the rejection is **not** about substance. It is about a red gate.

## The blocking failure (root cause, fully isolated)

1. **`claude-p-agent-wrapper-smoke.js:107`** asserts the default wrapper uses `stream-json`:
   `assert.equal(argv[argv.indexOf("--output-format") + 1], "stream-json", ...)` → **actual `json`**.

2. **Root cause — a non-hermetic test, not a code defect.** `claude-p-agent.js:47` sets `streamEnabled = process.env.CW_AGENT_STREAM !== "0" && process.env.CW_NO_STREAM !== "1"`. The test's `runWrapper` (`claude-p-agent-wrapper-smoke.js:77`) spawns with `env: { ...process.env, ...extraEnv, ... }` — it inherits the ambient environment **without scrubbing `CW_AGENT_STREAM`**. The release machine has `CW_AGENT_STREAM=0` exported, so the wrapper takes the legacy `--output-format json` branch (`claude-p-agent.js:53`) and the line-107 default-mode assertion breaks.

3. **Proven by isolation:** `env -u CW_AGENT_STREAM node …claude-p-agent-wrapper-smoke.js` → `ok` (exit 0). `CW_AGENT_STREAM=0 node …` → fails at line 107. Nothing in `v0.1.93..HEAD` touches `claude-p-agent.js` or this test — the failure is purely the ambient toggle leaking into a test that should control it explicitly.

This is exactly the fragility this release should have closed: it is all about `CW_AGENT_STREAM` semantics (the new `vendor-preflight.js` itself sets `CW_AGENT_STREAM: "0"` per call), yet a smoke that asserts the *default* stream mode is not hermetic against that very variable.

## Required fix (small, in-scope — make the gate green; do NOT cut another release for this)
1. Make `claude-p-agent-wrapper-smoke.js` hermetic. In `runWrapper` (line ~74-78), build the spawn env and **`delete env.CW_AGENT_STREAM; delete env.CW_NO_STREAM;`** before applying `extraEnv`, so the "default mode" case at line 107 tests the real default and each stream case sets the toggle explicitly. (Mirror the explicit-env discipline the new `vendor-preflight-smoke.js` already follows.)
2. Re-run `bash plugins/cool-workflow/scripts/release-gate.sh` and confirm it exits 0 with all 152 smokes green **with `CW_AGENT_STREAM=0` exported** (the real release-machine condition), not just with it unset.

## Secondary observations (not blocking, but fix in the same change)
- **Comment drift, `claude-p-agent.js:15-17`** says "default output is the legacy `--output-format json` … Set `CW_AGENT_STREAM=1` to opt in to stream-json," which contradicts the code at line 47 (stream is the default unless explicitly `"0"`) and the test's own expectation. Reconcile the comment with the actual default while you are in this file.
- **Man-page sync (verify):** the vendor routing changed shipped behavior (`gemini` now → opencode, new `builtin:gemini-cli` alias, deepseek model selection), but `docs/agent-delegation-drive.7.md` got only a trailing-version bump (+2). Confirm the documented builtin-vendor list still matches `builtin-templates.json`; update it in the same diff if it now lists the old routing.

This is the first review of this HEAD lineage; no gaming. Re-run the gate to green and resubmit — the substance already clears the bar; only the red gate stands in the way.

